4:28 PM Defendant Misha El Saludades Maier appeared by video, in custody.  Attorney Melissa Louise Barrette appeared by video for Misha El Saludades Maier.  Attorney Joel N Urmanski in court for State of Wisconsin. 
Court notes that this case was joined with case #21CF729 and does not believe that this case can be called without the other for victim's rights purposes.
State notes that bond has been posted in the other case and notice was only given for this case for today's bond hearing. Also notes that there are victims present on both cases today and believes bond can be addressed today.
State asks that victims be allowed to speak at this point and if victim's from case #21CF729 wish to speak, that they at least identify that they are victims on that case.
Court notes that cases are merged so will allow any victims to speak today.
Victim 3's Mother makes statement to Court - opposed to reduction in bond and asks Court to deny motion.
State objects to modification of bond and makes argument.
Defense makes argument in favor of bond motion - requesting lower bond of $40,000.00 cash bond.
Victim 3's Mother makes another statement to the Court.
Atty Barrette makes rebuttal argument as to statement and believes a non-monetary condition would be reasonable regarding remaining in WI during pendency of case.
Court does not believe bond is excessive due to exposure, risk of flight and allegations. 
Court denies bond motion.

4:06 PM Defendant Misha El Saludades Maier appeared by video, in custody.  Attorney Joel N Urmanski in court for State of Wisconsin.  Attorney Melissa Louise Barrette in court for Misha El Saludades Maier. 
950/Marsy's Law complied with. 
DA Urmanski notes multiple victims by zoom today.
State has reviewed Defense Motions in Limine -  
#1 - consuming alcohol is not another act and does not intend to produce any evidence as to other incidents. 
Defense notes other controlled substances at play and requests all other controlled substances be put under the umbrella of intoxicants.
Court grants #1 with that understanding.
#2 - All Discovery has been shared with Defense and State can provide a release for Defense to view if needed. Court grants #2.
#3 - State will share supplemental information as it is provided. Court grants #3.
Defense notes no litigation packet has been received regarding DNA testing and would like to receive before the Trial.
State notes no DNA evidence regarding identification - No amount significant enough for identification. Court will address in State's Motions.
#4 - State will share additional information with Defense as provided. Court grants. 
#5 - State will share additional information with Defense as provided. Court grants.
#6 - Court notes no expert has been named by Defense. Dfense notes no compliance with 45 days notice on expert re: DNA Analyst. Court will address in State's Motions.
#7 - Court grants sequestration with the exception of State's Officer. Court notes parties will have to admonish their witnesses.
DA Urmanski has no objection and notes that with Marsy's Law they cannot communicate with others regarding the case, but have the right to be able to attend all hearings including Trial and notes that some victims are juveniles and their parents therefore also have rights to be present but some parents are also witnesses and requests that permission is given to allow them to exercise that right. 
Atty Barrette objects.
Court will allow as long as sequestration order is followed.
#8 - State has provided a Witness List, but anticipates adding another Witness and will provide name to Defense and Court. Court grants. 
#9 - Victims will not be referred to as "victims" until closing arguments. State does not object, but requests "alleged victim" be allowed and notes that law enforcement will sometimes still state "victim" after many reminders.
Defense has no objection but believes that law enforcement can refrain from use. Court will grant and will take up in sidebar if use becomes egregious.
#10 - Granted by Court with the understanding that update will be done before Trial.
#11 and #12 Granted by the Court.
As to State's Motions in Limine - 
Defense has reviewed. No objections to #1-7 with exceptions to #5 and #7  that Defense does not have to provide Exhibits that will directly impeach Deft.
Court will grant #1-7 with understanding regarding impeachment.
#8- Defense believes able to provide information regarding relationships between Deft and witnesses due to establishing background and from small town.
Court grants consistent with Statute.
#9 - Panoramic evidence regarding intoxication already discussed. 
#10 - Atty Barrette notes that untruthful statements were made regarding location and does not believe it is another act and should be allowed in.
State believes statements lying about location specific to date/time of allegations is relevant to Defense and does not object.
#11 - Defense objects. Does not believe that Deft should automatically be considered a risk just because he is in custody.
State notes that device is not visible to Jury in any way and operator will also be in plain clothes. State believes with nature of allegations and amount and frequency that device should be worn.
Court will not order RACC belt - #11 denied.
#12 and #13 - State believes that behaviors that occurred leading up to incident would be brought in and does not object. Defense would like to reserve objection as to DNA, as litigation packet has not been received yet but does not anticipate that anything will be in packet that would cause a motion to be filed. State notes that behavior with other males should not be brought in. 
Court grants #12 and #13.
State notes Statute and requests Court to make a pretrial ruling. Court agrees that it needs to be brought by pretrial motion. Defense willing to bring offer of proof during the Trial outside of the Jury. Court grants. 
As to Count 1 on 22CF19-  Defense notes ongoing sexual activity and statements made by victim regarding consent - believes short of pretrial motions that certain statements should be able to be brought in.
State notes that due to age of victim consent is not relevant - believes Jury Instruction issue. Court will need to review closer and review Criminal Complaint.
#14 - Regarding DNA - Defense believes speculative and no relevant probative value if DNA is testified to. State notes 3 samples were tested
Court denies #14.
#15 - Granted by Court.
#16 - Defense has no objection. Court grants.
#17 - Defense objects - has received no notice that nurse is testifying in any expert manner. State notes medical record and statements guide nurse into examination and treatment. Nurse could testify after victim to provide consistent statements. Court Denies #17.
Jury Selection is Friday - double panel of Jurors.
State notes that Amendment might need to be made regarding ages but will let Judge and Counsel know prior to Trial.
